Project Business Statistics: E-news Express¶

Marks: 60

Define Problem Statement and Objectives¶

E-news Express has created a new landing page, and they are attempting to determine - statistically - whether the new landing page is more effective at gathering new subscribers. This testing is performed by splitting users into two equal sized groups of 50. The first group (control group) has the old landing pages serve to them, and the second group (treatment group) is served the new landing page. The objectives of this statistical analysis are found below:

  1. Perform exploratory data analysis on the dataset
  2. Do users spend more time on the new landing page than on the old landing page.
  3. Is the conversion rate for new subscribers on the new landing page higher than the old landing page.
  4. Does conversion depend on the language used? (use pd.crosstab())
  5. Is the mean time spent on the new page the same across different language users? (use ANOVA)

The purpose of this project is to perform A/B tesitng on 2 landing pages.

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(data=data, x=feature, palette="Paired", order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values())

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(100 * p.get_height() / total)  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()      # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(label, (x, y), ha="center", va="center", size=12, xytext=(0, 5), textcoords="offset points")  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

Null hypothesis =
  mean of time spent on the new and old landing page is the same.

Alternate hypothesis =
  mean of time spent on new landing page is greater.

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

Use the 2-sample t-test.

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

significance level = 0.05

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

In [46]:
y_old = df.where(df['landing_page'] == 'old').dropna()['time_spent_on_the_page']
y_new = df.where(df['landing_page'] == 'new').dropna()['time_spent_on_the_page']

Step 5: Calculate the p-value¶

In [47]:
from scipy import stats
In [48]:
stats.ttest_ind(y_old, y_new, equal_var = False, alternative = 'less')
Out[48]:
Ttest_indResult(statistic=-3.7867702694199856, pvalue=0.0001392381225166549)

Step 6: Compare the p-value with $\alpha$¶

0.000139 < 0.05

Step 7: Draw inference¶

The p-value is below a significance level of 0.05, meaning there is enough evidence to refute the null hypothesis.
This means that the mean of time spent on the new landing page is most likely greater.

A similar approach can be followed to answer the other questions.

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

Null hypothesis =
  Conversion rate on the new and old landing page is the same.

Alternate hypothesis =
  Conversion rate on new landing page is greater.

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

Use the proportions z-test.

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

significance level = 0.05

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

In [125]:
count_1 = df_conversion.where(df_conversion['landing_page'] == 'old').dropna()['converted'].value_counts().iloc[0]
total_amount_1 = count_1 + df_conversion.where(df_conversion['landing_page'] == 'old').dropna()['converted'].value_counts().iloc[1]
count_2 = df_conversion.where(df_conversion['landing_page'] == 'new').dropna()['converted'].value_counts().iloc[0]
total_amount_2 = count_2 + df_conversion.where(df_conversion['landing_page'] == 'new').dropna()['converted'].value_counts().iloc[1]
count = [count_1, count_2]
total_amounts = [total_amount_1, total_amount_2]

Step 5: Calculate the p-value¶

In [135]:
from statsmodels.stats.proportion import proportions_ztest
In [136]:
_, pvalue = proportions_ztest(count, total_amounts, alternative = 'smaller')
In [137]:
print(pvalue)

0.2049454484808052

Step 6: Compare the p-value with $\alpha$¶

0.2049454484808052 > 0.05

Step 7: Draw inference¶

Not enough evidence to refute the null hypothesis that the conversion rates are the same across both landing pages.

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

Null hypothesis =
  Time spent between landing pages is the same.

Alternate hypothesis =
  Time spent between landing pages is the different.

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

Use ANOVA

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

significance level = 0.05

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

In [224]:
english = df.where(df['language_preferred'] == 'English').dropna()['time_spent_on_the_page']
french = df.where(df['language_preferred'] == 'French').dropna()['time_spent_on_the_page']
spanish = df.where(df['language_preferred'] == 'Spanish').dropna()['time_spent_on_the_page']

Step 5: Calculate the p-value¶

In [226]:
from scipy.stats import f_oneway
In [228]:
_, pvalue = f_oneway(english, french, spanish)
In [229]:
print(pvalue)

0.8665610536012648

Step 6: Compare the p-value with $\alpha$¶

0.8665610536012648 > 0.05

Step 7: Draw inference¶

There is not enough evidence to refute the null hypothesis that the mean time spent on the page is the same across the sample distributions.

Conclusion and Business Recommendations¶

The mean time spent on the new landing page is greater. There is not enough evidence to show that the conversion rate is different across those landing pages; it is advisable to get a larger sample distribution to test this hypothesis in the future. Language seems to have no impact on conversion rates or time spent on landing page.
